<paragraph blockId="116.[151,1436,1878,2011]" lastBlockId="117.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="117" lastPageNumber="118" pageId="116" pageNumber="117">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1986,2011]" pageId="116" pageNumber="117">Notes.</emphasis>
Recorded nesting in oak galls, possibly from Massachusetts (
<bibRefCitation author="Packard" box="[961,1120,1986,2011]" firstAuthor="Packard" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" pagination="364 - 379" refId="ref97758" refString="Packard, A. S. (1867) The home of the bees. American Naturalist, 1, 364 - 379. https: // doi. org / 10.1086 / 270104" type="journal article" year="1867">Packard 1867</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Scott" box="[1139,1278,1987,2011]" firstAuthor="Scott" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" pagination="79 - 80" refId="ref101890" refString="Scott, V. (1993) Use of communal nest entrances by Osmia simillima (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae. The Great Lakes Entomologist, 26, 79 - 80." type="journal article" year="1993">Scott (1993)</bibRefCitation>
describes this species nesting communally in buried wood at a sandy site at Pictured Lakes National Lakeshore, Michigan. A nest in driftwood on the west shore of Lake Michigan was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Graenicher" box="[893,1102,188,213]" firstAuthor="Graenicher" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="153 - 167" refId="ref89503" refString="Graenicher, S. (1905) Some observations on the life history and habits of parasitic bees. Bulletin of the Wisconsin Natural History Society, 3, 153 - 167." type="journal article" year="1905">Graenicher (1905)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
